Your main issue is that you are completely building the `$DiskInfo` array before ever adding it to the `$HardwareInfo` object. When you finally do add it, it is already an array or collection, and you are assigning it to a property. A collection as a property will have the default output format of `{item1, item2, item3}`. For the desired output, you need to move the `Add-Member` command inside of the `foreach ($Disk in $HWDisks) {}` loop. Based on this code alone, `$DiskInfo` as an array is not necessary. See below for edits.

    Function Show-DiskInfo {
        $HWDisks =  Get-PhysicalDisk
    
        $HardwareInfo = New-Object PSCustomObject -Property @{
             Info = &quot;Disk Info&quot;
             &quot;----&quot; = &quot;----------------&quot;
        }
    
        foreach ($Disk in $HWDisks) {       
             $HardwareInfo |
                 Add-Member -MemberType NoteProperty -Name Disks -Value ($Disk.FriendlyName + ($Disk.size/1GB) + &quot; GB&quot;)
                }
        $HardwareInfo | Format-List Info,“----“,Disks
    }
    Show-DiskInfo


----------


**Alternative Approach:**

What I do not know is if you are trying to replicate `Format-Table` or `Format-List` output. My personal preference would be to create a custom object that stores property and value pairs. If you have multiple objects, you can either store them in an array within the function or output each object from the function. If the purpose of the function is to gather disk information and format the output, then you will need to manage the array within the function.

Regarding formatting, I would not use the disk info custom object properties to manage formatting. It creates an inconsistency within the object because now you have properties that serve no real purpose other than setting up your formatting. I would just use the format operator (`-f`) format the output.

    Function Show-DiskInfo {
        &quot;Info : Disk Info&quot;
        &quot;---- : ----------------&quot;
        foreach ($disk in Get-PhysicalDisk) {
            $obj = [PSCustomObject]@{
                     FriendlyName = $disk.FriendlyName
                     Size = $disk.Size/1GB
            }
            &quot;Disks : {0} ({1} GB)&quot; -f $obj.FriendlyName,$obj.Size
        }
    }
    Show-DiskInfo

